description.text: This has the original files for the Peon quadcopter along with my reimagined base with side walls. I'm sick of grass clippings getting in and around my components. Don't just print all the parts at once. Make sure you know which parts you want to use first. When you print the bottom canopy parts with the walls around you can start printing the bottom part in one color and then pause it and change the filament and finish printing the walls with a different color. That's how I got the two different colors. I would print at 100% infill. I just added ("New top canopy fixed") a new canopy for the top so it will not be so tight around the arm fixtures. Its possible to fit everything under ("very bottom 2 fixed") the first canopy I designed but some people are going to want more room plus you can flip the arms right side up. You can just use zip ties to hold the top canopy on if you want but some people won't like that because you have to cut them every time you open it up. The advantage is that if you crash the zip tie will break before any of the plastic breaks and its also easier to put together and take apart. Just buy a big bag of long and short zip ties for a few bucks. I also just added a STL file for a cover for the FrSky D4-R receiver if you want to put it underneath the quadcopter. The reason I did it is because I put all the ESC's inside the frame canopy and there was no more room left for the receiver as you can tell by the picture of the quadcopter underneath. Also if you use those shock absorbing landing gear you might want to put a piece of plastic in between the landing gear and the arms where the gap is with the screw. Otherwise if you tighten them to much it will break the plastic. Now if you mount the motors upside down that would not be necessary. Let me know how you like it.

title: Hello Kitty Bow with Holes for Necklace or Bracelet

description.text:
I haven't really seen any Hello Kitty bows around here, and the ones I have seen I'm not too impressed with. I decided to make my own, so here it is! Have fun! The only thing I ask is that you do not attempt to sell these, please. :D It was really small, so I enlarged it in solidworks. It was still pretty small, but you can enlarge it in MakerWare if you want it bigger. My preference is for it to be thin but large. Here's the specs for my most recent print:
X: 50.80 mm
Y: 41.24 mm
Z: 6.10 mm I like the thickness at 6.10 mm, no matter what size. I might adjust to be a tiny bit thicker if I were to make it any larger, but it's a decent thickness.

You can try what you like best, but I printed it at: Infill: 100%
Shells: 1
Layer Height: 0.1 Printed in red, and switched the filament for the border to be black. Wish there was a way to make the outer shell black as well, but that wouldn't work on my machine. Good luck! EDIT
I recently acquired a Replicator 2X, so now I can make the bow with 2 colors. This allowed me to make the sides black as well as the outline of the bow. I've updated the files to include 2 separate STL's; the inner and the outer part of the bow. What I did was add them both to MakerWare, center both of them on the build plate, then make sure that the inner bow is 3mm above the build plate (z). If you want to adjust the size (I know I did), the easiest way is to click on the uniform scaling option, adjust by a percentage and keep that consistent between both files, then unclick the uniform scaling option, and resize z. For my first attempt at this bow, printing in ABS, I used 125% uniform scale on both files, then changed the outer bow Z to 6.01mm. The inner bow Z was changed to 3mm. Let me know how it goes! I'll post a picture of my print once it's finished.

description.text:
I'm sharing this to thank everyone who has supported my ongoing Kickstarter campaign, Through a Scanner, Skulpturhalle, http://ThroughAScanner.com If you're already a backer: Thanks! Thanks for seeing its potential, and for helping to make it happen. Here's one of the British Museum's gems to tide you over while we wait--and hope--for the Skulpturhalle scans to materialize. I'll try to process and publish more scans I've already done at other museums while the Kickstarter is still running, to make my fundraising "updates" worthwhile. If you haven't heard of my project: My Kickstarter will suport me travelling to the Skulpturhalle Basel museum in Switzerland to 3D scan a collection of plaster casts of ancient Greek and Roman sculptures. Then I'll edit them for 3D printability and share it all here on Thingiverse. If you like the models I've scanned and shared so far, and want to help me keep at it, please consider supporting my project, and tell others about it. Please take a look at the project site: http://ThroughAScanner.com Thanks,
Cosmo - [email protected] - http://cosmowenman.com

Colossal bust of Ramesses II, the 'Younger Memnon' I captured this piece at the British Museum in October, 2012. I've printed it at around 4" tall, and cast another copy in bronze at around 10" tall -- the brightly colored version in the photo above. For more about my bronze casting, see my comments on 3D Scanning, 3D Printing, Bronze Casting, and the Art of the Living Dead (Ramesses II in bronze is for sale, btw.)

From the British Museum's web entry: Weighing 7.25 tons, this fragment of his statue was cut from a single block of two-coloured granite. He is shown wearing the nemes head-dress surmounted by a cobra diadem. The sculptor has used a slight variation of normal conventions to relate his work to the viewer, angling the eyes down slightly, so that the statue relates more to those looking at it. It was retrieved from the mortuary temple of Ramesses at Thebes (the 'Ramesseum') by Giovanni Belzoni in 1816. Belzoni wrote a fascinating account of his struggle to remove it, both literally, given its colossal size, and politically. The hole on the right of the torso is said to have been made by members of Napoleon's expedition to Egypt at the end of the eighteenth century, in an unsuccessful attempt to remove the statue. The imminent arrival of the head in England in 1818 inspired the poet Percy Bysshe Shelley to write Ozymandias: I met a traveller from an antique land
Who said: Two vast and trunkless legs of stone
Stand in the desart. Near them, on the sand,
Half sunk, a shattered visage lies, whose frown,
And wrinkled lip, and sneer of cold command,
Tell that its sculptor well those passions read
Which yet survive, stamped on these lifeless things,
The hand that mocked them and the heart that fed:
And on the pedestal these words appear:
"My name is Ozymandias, king of kings:
Look on my works, ye Mighty, and despair!"
Nothing beside remains. Round the decay
Of that colossal wreck, boundless and bare
The lone and level sands stretch far away. After its arrival in the British Museum the 'Younger Memnon' was perhaps the first piece of Egyptian sculpture to be recognized as a work of art by connoisseurs, who traditionally judged things by the standards of ancient Greek art. Source:
http://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/highlights/highlight_objects/aes/c/colossal_bust_of_ramesses_ii.aspx Wikipedia:
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Younger_Memnon
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ozymandias

This is not the sharpest of scans -- the original is ten to fifteen feet in the air, so I could only shoot it from a distance, and at very low angles. The lighting wasn't great either. (I'll have much better access, lighting, and results in the near-ideal setting at the Skulpturhalle!) I normally wouldn't publish a low-res scan like this, but the overall form is there, and unmistakable. And some of the hieroglyphs did come through. It makes for a nice, easy print so I thought it'd be worth sharing. (For higher quality scans more indicitive of what I'm shooting for at the Skulpturhalle, see these: http://thingiverse.com/CosmoWenman/collections/3d-scans-by-cosmo-wenman) Because the original was made from a single piece of stone, there's something scale-independent about the design, including the fracture. Even printed small, it looks plausible as a "real" object, as opposed to something like, say, a mini Eiffel tower. I've printed two copies for myself so far, one at 1/20th scale and another at 1/10th scale (in two parts). It makes for a stately little print. I don't think printing it full scale is in the cards any time soon, but I would like to print one at least human scale. I'll share those multi-part printable files here too when it's done.

Kickstarter Youtube video:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SUjvV4xV7NU

I've uploaded three files:  
A single piece print, set at 1/20th scale. It prints well hollow, with no external supports. There's just a tiny amount of sloppy overhang under this nose and one ear.  
A two-part print, set at 1/10th scale. This also prints well hollow, without external supports. (With the same very minor overhang slop.) These pieces are oriented to just barely fit within the build volume of a Replicator1. You shouldn't have to move or rotate them.

print_settings.Resolution:: .1mm layers for pea, .25mm layers for whistle body

description.text:
Inspired by the "Storm Whistle" I found by searching for whistles online, I created this thing. Print the pea first
You must drop the printed pea into the whistle's circular chamber while it's printing. Wait until the whistle has printed at least 10mm high (the base thickness is 2mm, and the pea is 8mm diameter).
I printed the pea using "spiral vase" mode. If you do not have that option with your slicer/printer, print with one shell, 0% infill (no infill). That will give you a nice, light, hollow pea for the whistle chamber. Believe it or not, it will (and needs to) print without support (the inside of the whistle needs to be hollow with no obstructions). This will test your printer's bridging capabilities. The bridging and next two layers may be a bit messy, but you should get a nice top surface.

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.1mm layers for pea, .25mm layers for whistle body

Infill:

0% for pea, 40% for whistle body

I didn't even bother uploading the first version; it was too wide (tall as printed), and required blowing way to hard to get a whistle sound.  So, for my second attempt (first uploaded here), I made it narrower, tweaked the airflow from the mouthpiece, and the barrel chamber's slot, and also printed the pea hollow.
I actually had to try several slight variations of the internal layout to get a decent whistling sound.  Unfortunately, there is too much "printing artifacts" (plastic deposited during movements) in the pea chamber of the one I printed, so it just whistles, but the pea doesn't really move around, so there is no pitch variation you would normally get with a pea whistle.
So, I'll be redesigning this to be printed in multiple parts that can be assembled so that the inside can be "cleaned up" after printing before assembly (and then you won't need to set an alarm to remember to drop the pea in while it's printing).

description.text:
Here's my design for what I consider the best Gimbal mount for the TBS discovery. By using decent propellers you will eliminate most of the course vibration meaning that the vibration that will reach your camera is normally very fine. The standard rubber grommet style mounts are not very good at eliminating these fine vibrations so it can be difficult to get a nice smooth picture. This mount allows you to slide four rubber grommet's over the front two standoff's and sandwich the mount between the frame plates and the outer part of the grommet, essentially isolating the mount from the frame. This gives a very firm mount (which makes more aggressive flying possible, check out midway through the second video), but still removes a large amount of the fine vibrations seen in most peoples videos. Here's some videos shot with this mount, to prove its effectiveness. Unfortunately my GoPro has seen better days so the video quality isn't all that great, but you get the idea. I'll have some 2.7k footage from my Xiaomi Yi sometime in the next few weeks once I've retuned the gimbal for it, so stay tuned!

description.text:
My Twoup's y-table has gotten loose and vent. So, I designed this as a replacement. Also, I wanted this lighter, to improve the print speed and quality.
Although I use the aluminum print bed in the picture, this design is compatible with the stock MDF print bed.

• Hillman Mending plate 9HL

    $3.48 for 6 pcs at my local Lowe's. This design uses 4 out of it.
    http://www.lowes.com/pd_364404-37672-884480___?productId=3478229

    If this is hard to obtain, I have included the PLA alternative in this design. However, the PLA may not be as strong or light as aluminum.

  • 8-32-1/2' Machine screw + nut : 8 pairs ( to hold the brackets to mending plates)
  • M3 x 20 screw + nut : 8 pairs (to hold the y-axis shaft)
  • (optionally) M4 x 20 + nut : 4 pairs ( to tighten the timing belt. The stock M4 x 16 screw HW10 can be also used, while tightening might be a bit challenge.)

description.header: Recycle from the original kit ( part name in the parenthesis )
description.text:
• 8mm x 290 ROD : 2 pcs ( FF)
  • M3 screw : 4 pcs ( HW11)
  • M3 nut : 4 pcs ( HW17)
  • Medium spring : 4 pcs ( HW12)
    • The QUBD's assemble manual says the HW11 & HW17 are M4 screw and nuts, but my kit came with M3.

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

This design assumes the PLA print grips the chrome shaft very tightly.
I use SainSmart's PLA to get the frame very hard, which I cannot skew or twist by my hands.
However, other PLA or other uncontrolled parameters may result differently. If this concerns you, try the followings, before print all the parts.
  • Print one of the brackets ( table_*.stl ), and one 'shaft_cap.stl'.
  • Sandwich a 8mm chrome shaft with them through M3 screws.
    (If you don't have the shaft handy, probably TwoUp's vertical rod may be easiest to try,
    instead of disassembling the gantry or print bed ).
  • Ensure this bracket holds tight enough that you can not move (neither rotate nor pull)
    • If the bracket cannot be tight enough, you may need a super-glue the frame later,
    or consider thing:815739, which has many diagonal supports.

Once the above concerns are addressed, print out the following parts.

  • shaft_cap 4 pcs

  • (option) support_bar_half 4 pcs

    This is an alternative for the mending plate. Use this only when they
    cannot be available. The PLA may not be as strong as the steal, though.

  • belt_spacer_3mm ~ 2 pairs ( 1 pair = 2pcs )

    This is to adjust the timing belt's height. No need to print for the original TwoUp.
    Print 1 pair if your y-axis shaft are raised 3mm with a bearing pillow (such as thing:591345)
    Print 2 pairs for higher position ( e.g. use SCS8UU bearing instead of stock LM8LUU)

  • others : print 1 pcs each

1. Assemble the north frame Combine table_ne and table_nw with the 2 mending plate with 8-32 screw and nuts.
Sandwich the y-axis shaft with the shaft_cap with m3x20 screw. (picture 1 below) Picture 1: Bracket close up. 8-32 screwes for mending plates. M3 screws for the y-axis shaft. 2. Assemble the south frame Repeat for table_se and table_sw. The assembled frame should look like below. Ensure the frame is very rigid.
Put the frame in a very flat surface (e.g. kitchen tile) to ensure the frame is align with it.
Ensure the frame doesn't twist nor skew. Picture 2 : Put the frame on a very flat surface ( e.g. kitchen title). Ensure it doesn't twist or skew. 3. Replace the stock y-table frame with the assembled frame. 4. Attach the timing belt Attach the timing belt with M4 screws. If the y-axis shaft are raised in your TwoUp (e.g. thing:591345), use the "belt_spacer_3mm", as needed.(picture 3 below) You can still use the stock M4 screws to thread down, if you print a thinner version of belt holder (e.g. thing:987666). Using the longer M4 screws and nuts is more secure, though. PIcture 3: Use as many spacers as you need to adjust the timing belt height.

description.text: Note that this was designed for the original MPCNC Z rail mount. This won't fit the newest MPCNC version "525" Makita rt0701c 1.25 HP variable speed compact router tool mount for the wonderful Mostly Printed CNC. The holder is sized for US EMT conduits. This router is much more powerful and much quieter than the Harbor Freight flexshaft grinder and is variable from 10K to 30K RPM. Note that the Makita only comes with a 1/4" collet. I got a high quality 1/8" collet from: http://www.elairecorp.com/makitaroutercollets.html. It supposedly has a very low runout. A 1/4" to 1/8" reducer can also be used. The weight is 3lb 1oz. The clamp holes should fit #6x3/4" or M3x18mm bolts. This was my first Autodesk Fusion 360 design so I did not try to get too fancy. Next time I will try for captive nuts. The Fusion 360 source is included. I'm proud of how close I got the spindle center to the Z axis. There is really only 2mm or so to spare! A tradeoff is that the on/off switch is a bit hard to get to depending on the Z position and the rotation of the router. The speed control dial is easily reachable. Printed at 0.3mm/layer, 30% infill in PETG from the Microcenter (Cambrige, MA store). About 4 hours to print on a Robo3D with an E3DV5. Thanks for inspiration from shnads' metric tube mount: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1008647. Update (11/8/15): I suggest mounting it upside down from the position in the photos to slightly reduce the Z length and associated torque. I am also now using Camar0's Middle Rigid Bracket Add on and Allted's Middle Z Ridgid. See: http://www.thingiverse.com/make:169149 Update (12/14/15)): I jury rigged a simple vacuum hose holder by extending the three screws to hold a 1.5x3.5 piece of thin hardwood plywood. A piece of PVC pipe was tie wrapped to the plywood. Used a file to groove the pipe in three places for the tie wraps to grip better. A 1.25" vacuum hose fits into the pipe. I velcroed a clear piece plastic (acetate?) from a box window to guide the airflow. See build photo in: http://www.vicious1.com/forum/topic/cosx2y2-milled-in-wood-post-1/ SteveC

description.text:
Receiving lots of greeting cards at Christmas or for birthdays is great but they either take up a lot of space on a bench (and you can only see the front ones) or you have to go to the trouble of stringing them up... the 'Card Stacker' provides a quick and easy alternative way to display your cards.
Just print out a set of 'Card Stackers' and stack them up... going 'high rise' saves space and lets you see more cards more easily. 
Each 'Card Stacker' has very thin walls so they are a lightweight print that uses very little filament. They should work with almost all greeting cards. Most 3D printers that print fine features accurately will print these well... but refer to the instructions for print details.
The most important usage tips are:
Always use a base 'Card Stacker' as this provides a solid platform... as cards can curl.
Make sure your stack stays straight... refer to the images to see how to adjust your 'Card Stackers'. They can be moved to help ensure the stack goes straight up so it is stable and won't easily topple over. Done right you can readily stack 4, 5 or even 6 tall. 3 is easy...
Note: If you like this check out the rest of my practical and fun designs!

Notes: The 'Card Stacker' has thin walls so print using 2 or 3 shells and high infill as suggested. Printed well, they should have clean grooves to slip your cards into... check they are clear before trying to stack up your cards. If your grooves are not clear and can't be cleaned out easily increase the scale slightly to increase the internal clearances (groove width) Print several 'Card Stackers' at once as you will need them... they use very little filament.

This is a printable LM8UU equivalent bearing.
It is used in place of a conventional steel LM8UU.
I designed it so that it can be used as a replacement for Ultimaker style sintered-brass bushings. This is also me trying to place a concept of using the easily available 4mm ptfe tube as bearing surfaces in Repraps. Looking forward to suggestions and remixes! This is also one of my first attempts at parametric design. There could be a lot of errors. Do point it out.

Cutting the 4x2mm PTFE tube
  • Cut a 28mm length of 4mm PTFE tubing (2mm internal dia). The same used for 1.75mm bowden extruder.
  • use a xacto knife or modelling blade to cut the PTFE tube longitudinally along the center. (careful not to cut your self) I am planning on building a small printable tool with a blade attached to do this accurately and safely.
    • Do tell me if you need photos of this step. Inserting the 'half-tube' into the bearing case There are helical grooves in the casing.
    Push the cut tube pieces into the grooves.
    You will need to take care that the PTFE piece does not bend outside the casing.
    A little persuasion and care will do the job. Reaming and sanding if required After the tube-pieces are pushed in, you might need to further push the tubes into the grooves using some tool.
    Usually a (closed) nose-tip pliers works great.
    You could also file it down with a fine grit round merchant file.

I decided to make a version of the sword from the 80's cartoon. As an exercise for using sketchup and for a present for a friend's birthday. Just in time for the impending "event" (T-cats reboot), this Friday. I spent a lot of time on the model. I started with a few models from 3dwarehouse. None were very good for printing, or scaled well for actually holding. All of them relied on textures for details that wouldn't show up after printing. Initially the model came out too small. Then it didn't fit the hand well. Once it was sized and shaped correctly I had to work out how it could be chopped up to fit my build envelope. The latest version has location holes to help line up parts and glue together. It seems that the blade has benefited greatly from the interior channel. Even without the filament the blade is stronger. I'm working on another version with an insert for the eye and an insertion slot for the blade. So that the whole sword can be printed by colors: grip, blade, eye, jewel. Finished sword is about 45 inches (1145mm) from pommel to tip.
Oh and time for print @ 30mm/s min layer time of 20 secs:
6x blade pieces 5 hours

Update V2:
Added an update eye holder piece, with an insertion hole for the blade, the blade can be printed (in an optional extra color) and sanded/cleaned/finished then inserted into the holder. The insertion point's clearance hasn't been tested, but should be close. Might need sanding cleaning for the blade to fit. Also the new holder has inserts for the eye and cat emblem, which can be printed in two colors using the whole pause and swap method when it first starts printing the upper portion. This is also not printed yet but should be good. I'll print these and repport back later today. So for this, obviously instead of eye-holder.stl you'd use eye-holderV2 and the inserts. One of each or two of the same one. Switching to work in progress.

Update V3:
Found a small geometry problem in the eye holder as well as the fact that the thin ring (around the eye/cat image) was too thin to print nicely so changes to the inserts as well. Apologies if this print is too tall, I looked up the build envelope for a stock cupcake and fixed the model to stay under the published height of 130mm but if you have trouble with that use the V3 eye holder and the new shorter blade pieces.
Removed the original eye holder to reduce confusion. Any combined print can be exported from the sketchup.

Update V4: Added the center channel for using threaded rod or double ended threaded studs. The hole is a 3mm and can be drilled out to a larger dim if need be. I've left the other registration holes for those that prefer to use that. Also reversed the extrusion on the cat-insert to get around skeinforge's refusal to fill thin features. Prints much nicer. If you've already printed one, this one is a big improvement (see photo).

Print the parts out, clean and glue or weld together with acetone. There are channels for 3mm filament locators if you choose to use them. 
Also from my various prints, I determined that the blade pieces are stronger with the filament channel running up through it. Whether you put the filament in it or not. It forces the blade to be printed with a more solid column running up it which tends to make it stronger. You might also want to print the blade at a higher infill than usual.
I used Skeinforge's multiply for the cross pieces, blade pieces, and grip pieces. It slices a lot faster than making a printing plate.

Update
If you want a blade that isn't going to snap along a layer I recommend the following:
1: Tweak your setup to make interior holes the correct dimension (and/or drilling the holes out).
2: Run a piece of filament or preferably 1/8th inch steel rod from hardware store through the channel of the blade pieces.
3: When the pieces are all glued (with acetone or acetone/ABS mixture) gently sand the joints being sure to lay the blade on a long supportive surface.
4: Lightly paint the entire blade with acetone to weld the layers into one unit. 
5: Sand and finish (paint or color).
6: Fight Ancient Spirits of Evil.

title: MP CNC Control Panel With Mode Switch

description.text:
Design files for the control panel on my RAMPS 1.4-based MP CNC.
The thing was designed for the following components: https://www.gira.de/gebaeudetechnik/produkte/steckdosen/steckdosen-wgap.html
http://www.ebay.de/itm/251299028015?_trksid=p2060353.m2749.l2649&ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT
http://www.ebay.de/itm/121671542188?_trksid=p2060353.m2749.l2649&ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT After printing I realized that it's a good idea to mount the setup on spacers and "hide" all the previous chaotic wiring underneath the panel. The control panel features a "mode switch" which lets the user select between 3D printing, laser engraving and milling mode conveniently. That way fewer re-wiring is necessary if one wants to use the machine for different things. It's a multitool after all ;) A picture of a hand-drawn wiring diagram was also uploaded. In 3D printing mode you simply have D10 on RAMPS 1.4 routed through to the hot end terminals pre-mounted in the Z axis and D9 is routed through to thee plastic cooling fan. In Laser mode the same 2 wires used for the hotend are swithed over to the D9 MOSFET to use a laser as described here: http://jtechphotonics.com/?page_id=1503 In milling mode the D9 MOSFET is routed through to a 12V relay to switch a mains outlet box on and off using M106 S255 (on) and M107 S0 (off). Don't forget the back EMF diode or else the MOSFET will die! An LED with current limiting resistor would be a nice addition to indicate the spindle status.

Direct drive extruder for E3D v6 1.75mm hot end. The included X-carriage is compatible with Prusa i3. The extruder is designed so that the hot end is as close as possible to the x-carriage for maximum rigidity and build area. There are optional mounts for LJ12A inductive bed probe and 5015S filament cooling turbine - highly recomended. I started with this design: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:147705 and redisigned it completely, since I found it flexes too much under high extrusion speeds and reduces build area. The drive gear is a bit inaccesible due to the stepper motor being in front, but I haven't found this to be a problem. The filament can be loaded by inserting it right to the drive gear and then extruding about 70mm. You will need:
  • Nema 17 stepper motor
  • MK8 Drive gear
  • 40mm fan
  • 5015S turbine fan (recomended)
  • LJ12A inductive bed probe (optional)
  • 5x10x4mm ball bearing
  • Some M3 and M4 nuts and bolts
  • a spring, minimal internal diameter: 4mm
    • The extruder works extremly well with classic filaments like PLA and ABS. I haven't tried any flexible filaments yet. Note: Some parts in the pictures are mirrored. I suggest you mirror them according to your printer location for the best accesibility.

description.text:
Bonjour, Je suis un grand fan de l'imprimante Micro Delta de chez EmotionTech depuis que je l'ai découverte, elle est peu encombrante, très précise et polyvalente. Elle est aussi très abordable et je la trouve trop belle. Je l'ai modifiée plusieurs fois et, au fur et à mesure de son utilisation et des maintenances, j'ai accumulé plusieurs pièces en double.
J'ai donc voulu en fabriquer une autre... Voici donc ma version de la micro delta. Toutes les pièces sont imprimées en PLA et avec ma première micro delta. J'ai essayé de garder au maximum les mêmes cotes que celles de la micro delta d'origine afin que celles ci puissent être interchangeables.
Les parties mécaniques et électroniques sont également les mêmes et toute la visserie est standard. Les deux plateaux sont donc en quatre parties assemblées avec des vis de 5x60.
Les supports de moteurs sont directement intégrés au plateau supérieur.
J'ai aussi modifié le système d'extrusion du filament pour rendre son changement et la maintenance plus facile.
J'ai modélisé une nouvelle version des supports pour biellettes, ils sont un peu plus sobres et en une seule partie. Les roulements linéaires y sont logés de force.
J'ai juste allégé un peu les tendeurs de courroies mais j'ai gardé le système d'origine qui est très bien pensé.
J'ai modélisé un support de bobine horizontal assez large pour s'adapter à toutes les tailles de bobines que j'ai eu jusqu'à présent (même les chinoises un peu plus larges). Mais je pense que je proposerai un support vertical prochanement.
J'avais déjà posté ma version du corps d'extrusion, il permet d'adapter le hotend de chez Fourmix et rend la maintenance plus facile...
Et enfin j'ai ajouté quelques détails comme des fixations pour les cables et un bouton d'alimentation.
Je suis en train de modéliser un support pour l'écran LCD. J'espère que vous aimerez les modifications que j'ai faites. Vous pourrez trouver toutes les pièces détachées dont vous avez besoin sur le site de reprap france :
http://www.reprap-france.com/categorie/319-pieces-detachees N'hésitez pas à me contacter si vous avez besoin d'autres informations. Merci beaucoup à toute l'équipe de EmotionTech de m'avoir soutenu et aidé dans ce projet.

Pour fixer les courroies aux supports de biellettes, c'est un peu le même principe que sur la version de la micro delta d'origine, il faut faire deux petites boucles aux extrémités de la courroie avec des liens en plastique. En effet, le plateau qui sert de support d'impression peut chauffer relativement fort et les vis en métal qui le tiennent conduisent bien la chaleur et risqueraient de ramolir les pièces en PLA où elles sont fixées. C'est vrai que j'aimerais bien avoir un plateau un peu plus grand parfois mais en y pensant pendant la phase de modélisation, on arrive à dépasser cette contrainte et à imprimer de grandes pièces en plusieurs parties. (Comme la plupart de mes réalisations sur Thingiverse...)

Comme j'avais plusieurs pièces en double, je me suis dit que ça ne me coûterai pas beaucoup plus cher de me fabriquer une deuxième imprimante complète. Malheureusement, je ne m'y connais pas du tout en programmation. C'est aussi pour ça que pour mon projet,jai gardé la structure de la première micro delta. J'ai amélioré tout ce que je pouvais dans les limites de mes compétences et j'ai gardé le firmware de EmotionTech.
Par contre ton idée est super de vouloir fabriquer une "micro" delta XL et je serais ravi de t'aider dans ton projet pour la partie conception et modélisation si tu as besoin.

Bonjour,
Oui je te conseille vraiment la micro delta, elle est très compacte par rapport à son volume d'impression. Elle est aussi précise et très facile à régler (pas de réglages au niveau matériel : donc moins d'une minute via Repetier)
En plus, tu peux la rendre complètement autonome avec l'écran lcd disponible sur reprap-france.com (Il n'y a plus aucun bug avec le dernier firmware)
Je te conseille d'aller sur le site de EmotionTech pour télécharger le pdf de la notice de montage de la micro delta d'origine. Sur ma version, j'utilise les mêmes pièces mécaniques donc il te suffit de comparer avec les pièces dont tu dispose déjà.
Sur ma version, tu auras besoin de trois roulements linéaires supplémentaires, de deux fan 60x60, et d'un deuxième plateau.
Sinon j'ai installé le Hotend de chez Fourmix sur ma deuxième micro delta, il est vraiment super...
Normalement, tous les Hotends sont compatibles avec le corps d'extrusion que j'ai modélisé mais n'hésite pas à me contacter si tu as un problème au montage.
(Je te conseille aussi d'utiliser les thermistances de chez EmotionTech pour ne pas avoir à changer tous les paramétrages)
N'hésite pas à les contacter pour leur parler de ton projet, toute l'équipe est super sympa, ils sont hyper reactifs et donnent de très bon conseils.
Tiens moi au courant de l'avancée de ton projet.
À bientôt.

description.text: I have been interested in all of the multicolor projects being posted lately. Rather than trying to join different color filaments or utilize sharpies, I have gone with an "old-school" approach from the model car kits I assembled as a kid.  I printed out the different colors as different parts. Not much rocket science here.  Cupcake CNC #806 still produces a low res, pixilated version of the real thing (also shown in the picts at left).

I printed the base in green, the body in rust and the top in white (not "natural"). All of the filaments used were from 3dprinterstuff.com. The top is trial fitted and then rapidly inserted up through the body of the tower into the waiting molten, hot-melt glue. The base is then attached with hot-melt glue as well.

title: 2015 Sunhokey Prusa i3 extruder heatsink cooling duct

description.text:
This is the first part I designed to improve my 3D printing. It increased airflow around the Bowden extruder heatsink to make sure the heat from the hotend won't reach to the upper body which will soften the filament and causing blocks.
One of the attached pictures shows the bump caused by extra heat from the hot end.
Note: I designed this part in solidworks. Wasn't sure which side should be the first layer. So you need to turn 270 degree on Y axis when you do slicing. (To sit the fan mounting surface on the bed).

Rafts:

No

No

0.2mm

Infill:

40%

Notes: bed: 60C
hotend: 230C
Printing Speed: 30mm/s for infill and perimeter.

comments.text: I printed this as one of the first useful prints and an upgrade to my Sunhokey Prusa i3.  Nice design.  Unfortunately I snapped one of the side pieces playing around with it.  To me it seemed too loose against the coils and I was trying to ever so slightly bend it.  PLA doesn't bend, I should have known it wouldn't flex.  I'm still new to 3D printing.  Also I only used 30% infill instead of the recommended 40%. 0.2 layer height.    That 10% more infill could make all the difference, i don't know.  If it is printed with either the top or bottom against the bed (as it normally loads in the slicer) then it would be stronger but this would require support.  I've glued the broken one for now.  One day I may try one in the original orientation with support.  Thanks for a good design.

comments.text: i re-printed this again with the top against the bed, instead of the fan.  I used supports to do this.  This has the lines running horizontally when it is installed, instead of vertically.  This made the part a lot stronger where it is thinnest.  It also clamps on stronger.  In lieu of this if this was re-mixed with some horizontal ribs in that area it would be stronger and still easy to print.  I don't think the ribs would interfere with anything.

This was my entry into the Moat Boat Paddle Battle at Maker Faire NY 2015. This boat did not win but I'm happy to share my observations that could make it better.

Notes: The hydrofoils require supports. You could break this model apart and print all of the pieces without support but for me, I didn't want to spend extra time modeling the connection points so I decided to just print as one piece and worry about removing the supports later.

Removing Supports While the front hydrofoils are strong enough to support the weight of the boat and stay stiff in the water, they are thin enough to flex. Take extra care in removing the supports so you don't break the hydrofoils off. For the prop, I used the same mechanical design you find on rubberband-powered planes. I took a thick paperclip, straightened it and then turned one end into a loop for the rubberband. The other end went through the housing in the back and into the prop. I drilled completely through the prop and cut in a notch where the end of the paperclip came though and then bent into place. You may need to drill out the hole for the paperclip driveshaft to make sure it's a clean hole.

Designing The Boat After checking out previous boat designs for the Paddle Battle, I wanted to create something unique. The previous winner used a propeller instead of a paddle so I decided to do the same, although I printed my propeller instead of buying a thin plastic one. I've always been amazed by hydrofoils so I wanted to include them in my design. I didn't expect the boat to get completely out of the water on them, but I also knew I needed something to keep the boat tracking straight. Note: The torque of the propeller causes the boat to list to the right so the design needs modification to correct this. The hull is a pretty typical boat shape. If I were to change it, I might make it a little lighter/smaller. It might also benefit from being wider and a bit shallower. By the way, check out the full race/design rules here: http://www.moatboatpaddlebattle.com/rules/
